: 1722271626:0;To stop an Electron app that was started with the `alias G1` command, you need to identify the process and kill it. Here's how you can do it:\
\
1. **Identify the Process**: Use `ps` or `pgrep` to find the process ID (PID) of the Electron app. Since your Electron app was started with `npm`, you can look for `npm` processes and identify the one related to your app.\
\
   ```bash\
   pgrep -f "npm start"\
   ```\
\
   Alternatively, you can use `ps` and filter for `npm`:\
\
   ```bash\
   ps aux | grep "npm start"\
   ```\
\
   This will give you the PID(s) of the `npm` process running your Electron app.\
\
2. **Kill the Process**: Once you have the PID, use `kill` to stop the process.\
\
   ```bash\
   kill <PID>\
   ```\
\
   Replace `<PID>` with the actual PID of the process. If there are multiple PIDs or the process does not stop with a standard `kill`, you might need to use `kill -9`:\
\
   ```bash\
   kill -9 <PID>\
   ```\
\
3. **Optional Script for Stopping**: You can create an alias or script to automate stopping your Electron app. HereŌĆā\B9s an example alias that finds and kills the `npm start` process:\
\
   ```bash\
   alias G1_stop='pkill -f "npm start"'\
   ```\
\
   Add this to your shell configuration file (`~/.zshrc`, `~/.bashrc`, etc.) and reload it:\
\
   ```bash\
   source ~/.zshrc  # or ~/.bashrc, depending on your shell\
   ```\
\
   Then, you can use `G1_stop` to stop your Electron app.\
\
If you have a specific way to start the app or additional details about the process, let me know, and I can adjust the instructions accordingly!c
